com.salesforce.omakase.ast.extended

Class ConditionalAtRuleBlock

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.salesforce.omakase.ast.AbstractSyntax
      • com.salesforce.omakase.ast.atrule.AbstractAtRuleMember
        • com.salesforce.omakase.ast.extended.ConditionalAtRuleBlock
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    AtRuleBlock, AtRuleMember, StatementIterable, Syntax, Broadcastable, Writable, Iterable<Statement>

    public final class ConditionalAtRuleBlock
extends AbstractAtRuleMember
implements AtRuleBlock
    An extension to the standard CSS syntax that allows for conditional at-rules.

    Example of a conditional at-rule: 

      @if(ie7) { .test{color:red} }

    This block will output its inner statements if its condition is contained within the set of "true" condition strings, as specified by a ConditionalsConfig. Negation may be specified on conditions using !. Multiple conditions may be specified using ||.

    For more information on using and configuring conditionals see the main readme file.

    See Also:
    Conditionals, ConditionalsRefiner

      • ConditionalAtRuleBlock

        public ConditionalAtRuleBlock(int line,
                              int column,
                              Iterable<Conditional> conditionals,
                              Iterable<Statement> statements,
                              ConditionalsConfig config)
        Creates a new ConditionalAtRuleBlock instance with the given conditions, statements and config object.

        The given config contains the set of strings that are the "true" values/conditions. During output of the CSS source, this block and its contents will only be written out if its condition matches what is in the config (or vice versa if the negation operator is used).

        Note that this matching is case-sensitive (everything should be lower-cased).

        It is acceptable for the given config to change its set of true conditions, allowing the outputting of multiple variations of the CSS source from a single parse operation. For example, set the true conditions, write out the source, change the true conditions, write out the source again, etc.

        Parameters:
        line - The line number.
        column - The column number.
        conditionals - The list of conditionals.
        statements - The inner statements of the block. These will be printed out if the condition is contained within the trueConditions set.
        config - The ConditionalsConfig instance.

      • write

        public void write(StyleWriter writer,
                  StyleAppendable appendable)
           throws IOException
        Description copied from interface: Writable
        Outputs this Writable's string representation.

        Important notes for implementation:

        Do not use the StyleWriter in an attempt to write direct content (Strings, chars, etc...). Use the StyleAppendable.

        The StyleWriter should be used to make decisions based on writer settings (e.g., compressed vs. verbose output mode), as well as for writing inner or child Writables. Do not call the this method method directly on inner or child Writables! That would bypass any overrides that are set on the StyleWriter. Use StyleWriter.writeInner(Writable, StyleAppendable) instead.

        Specified by:
        write in interface Writable
        Parameters:
        writer - Writer to use for output settings and for writing inner Writables.
        appendable - Append direct content to this StyleAppendable.
        Throws:
        IOException - If an I/O error occurs.

        public void propagateBroadcast(Broadcaster broadcaster,

        Description copied from interface: Broadcastable
        Broadcasts or rebroadcasts all child units using the given Broadcaster.

        The broadcast will only occur for a unit if its Status matches the given Status.

        Implementers should call Broadcastable.propagateBroadcast(Broadcaster, Status) on child units and SyntaxCollections first, then use the broadcaster to broadcast itself. All of this should be wrapped in a check to ensure the Status matches.
